<tt>Tue Nov 11  0:18:32 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
It's a little after nine PST.  Let me you wish you and all the others a happy Veterans Day.  My sincere wishes to all of you.<br><br>
I believe that veterans in parades has decreased in most cities and towns across the country.  I know of many WWII and Korean vets are, simply, too old to march with rifles and flags anymore.  Their bodies can't do it.<br><br>
Patriotism has, and should, have different viewpoints.  I, sometimes, get angry, at the veterans organizations for for not joining together at the top and hopefully the rank and file would meld into one organization.  I think that would be a positive step in the right direction for all who wore the uniforms of the United States.  I know of a few young (we are no longer that young) who would like the bickering to go away.<br><br>
This is the information age, and petty differences should no longer be acceptable.<br><br>
We are diifferent in one small way, and I repeat the word small.  My sympathies are liberal, but I feel there is little, if any differences in our hearts.  I kid my friends and tell them that I am a &quot;radical&quot; middle of the roader.  It sometimes gets a laugh, most times not.  I want my child to live in a tolerant society.  Oops, my naivete struck again, where we can appreciate the efforts of all who believe in personal freedom and that the struggle for a better future is equal or more important than the pleasures of today.<br><br>
I am sure that we will both wake up tomorrow and feel proud that we both stood up for an ideal that is more important than we are.<br><br>
Paul
